  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Following the Rhyme of Choe Sa-rip at Cheonsu Temple
  author: Hong Eon-bak
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Deep runs the stream, thick grow the willows, and mother crows take flight.
    The shaded path lies green before us as we turn our horses homeward.
    What use, after all, are fame and fortune?
    Looking back, fifty-two years have slipped away.
    Circled together we play at pitching arrows, light they fly.
    Clear spirits stir in us, growing drunk on the desire to depart.
    Wandering here and there beside you, we have grown into two old men.
    This joy of living—there is nothing wrong with it.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The title indicates this is a poem written in response to another poem by Choe Sa-rip, following the same rhyme scheme. This was a common poetic practice in Classical Chinese and Korean literary circles.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'fifty-two years' is a personal reflection by the poet on the passage of time and his own aging.
  - key: ''
    value: Touhu (投壺) was an ancient Chinese game of skill where players attempted to toss arrows into a pot from a distance, often played by scholars during leisure.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem contrasts worldly ambitions with the simple pleasures of friendship, nature, and old age—a common theme in East Asian literati culture.
